The paper deals with streaming algorithms, which are typically studied in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The focus on randomized algorithms and their behavior on multiple executions suggests that cs.CC (Computational Complexity) may also be a relevant sub-category. The use of sketching algorithms and norm estimation suggests cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) as possible sub-categories. Finally, the study of lower bounds for multi-pseudo-deterministic algorithms suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as another possible sub-category.
